		<item>
		<title><![CDATA[“Miss, who taught the first teacher?”]]></title>
		<link>https://teacherplus.org/2026/2026/march-2026/miss-who-taught-the-first-teacher/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 04:46:16 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Kumar]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://teacherplus.org/?p=50059</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Priyanka Soman</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong><mark style="color:#9b51e0">Tiffin Box Musings is a collection of reflections that arrive without a timetable, a lesson plan, or a clearly labelled theme – much like a teacher’s thoughts during a busy school day. These pieces are drawn from classrooms, corridors, memories, questions, and those small moments that stay behind long after the bell rings. They do not promise conclusions, only curiosity. The one thing they have in common is learning – sometimes planned, often unexpected, and frequently delivered by students when the teacher least expects it. These musings are simply the everyday thoughts of a teacher who is still learning, one tiffin break at a time.</mark></strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Have you ever been caught off guard by a child’s question? You’re midway through a perfectly structured lesson, feeling rather pleased that everyone seems attentive, when a small hand goes up:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“Miss, who taught the first teacher?”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Suddenly, you’re silenced. Your PowerPoint slide on the water cycle fades into irrelevance. The room shifts. And for a moment, teacher and students are simply fellow travellers in the strange and wonderful business of life.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><mark style="color:#0693e3">As J. Krishnamurti once said,&nbsp;<em>“The whole of life, from the moment you are born to the moment you die, is a process of learning.”</em>&nbsp;Not memorizing, not passing exams – but learning.</mark></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Cleverness or intelligence?</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Let me ask you: what do you think education is? Passing exams? Moving up a grade? Collecting certificates?</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>We often confuse these things. But cleverness is not intelligence. Cleverness is knowing that the capital of France is Paris. Intelligence is realizing that if you forget your packed lunch on a school trip to Paris, no amount of geography will save you.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><em><mark style="color:#0693e3">“Intelligence is the capacity to perceive the essential, the what is; and to awaken this capacity, in oneself and in others, is education.”</mark></em></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Think back to your own schooling. How much of what you memorized for exams do you actually use now? Be honest. Did Pythagoras’ theorem rescue you when your washing machine broke down? Probably not.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>The left brain, the right brain… and lunch</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Our system loves the left side of the brain: logic, numbers, reading, writing. Important, yes. But what about the right side: creativity, rhythm, intuition?</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>I once had a student who turned an entire maths problem into a rap. Did he get full marks? No. Did the rest of the class finally understand fractions? Absolutely.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Another child asked:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“Miss, if the left brain controls the right hand and the right brain controls the left hand, who controls lunch?”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>I laughed. But isn’t there wisdom in that? Life isn’t just logic; it’s also laughter, music, movement, and mystery.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><em><mark style="color:#0693e3">“Education is not the cultivation of memory, but the cultivation of intelligence which is the capacity to think freely and without fear.”</mark></em></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Perhaps children understand this far better than adults do.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":50061,"width":"744px","height":"auto","sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none","align":"center"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter size-full is-resized"><img src="https://teacherplus.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Tiffin-box-musings.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-50061" style="width:744px;height:auto" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Illustration: Shilpy Lather</figcaption></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Lessons beyond the textbook</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Think of a time you learnt something unforgettable outside the classroom. For me, it was a school hike. The children slipped, stumbled, and giggled their way up a muddy hill. One girl reached out and said to me, “Don’t worry Miss, you can use my water bottle when you faint.” Mortifying, but strangely moving.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The hike was steep, muddy, and full of slips, but it was there that true learning happened. Children helped each other, shared snacks, and told stories of home. Bonds were formed not from an essay on “teamwork”, but from the lived experience of needing one another.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><em><mark style="color:#0693e3">“The function of education is to create human beings who are integrated and therefore intelligent.”</mark></em></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>And I have seen this integration – mind, heart, and body – most clearly in such lived moments.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>What about you? Do you remember a school memory that taught you more than a textbook ever did?</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>The questions that linger</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Children have an incredible way of asking questions that stop us in our tracks:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>“Miss, if exams test what we remember, why don’t you ask us what we had for lunch last week?”</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>“Miss, if time is money, why doesn’t the bank give us more holidays?”</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>“Miss, what if the Earth is just someone else’s marble?”</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Can you feel it? That pause, that moment of silence. These are not questions with tidy answers. They are invitations to wonder. And perhaps that is where real education begins.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><em><mark style="color:#0693e3">“It is no measure of health to be well adjusted to a profoundly sick society.”</mark></em></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Perhaps children’s questions remind us not to adjust too comfortably to a broken education system, but to dream of something new.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Where do we go from here?</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>It would be easier to keep things mechanical. Teach, test, tick the boxes. But easier is not better. Children are not cupboards to be filled or factory products to be standardized. They are individuals – each with their own rhythms, curiosities, and gifts.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>So, here’s the question I leave with you:&nbsp;<strong>what would education look like if we stopped asking children to be clever, and instead encouraged them to be intelligent, creative, compassionate human beings?</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><mark style="color:#0693e3"><em>“The whole purpose of education is to awaken intelligence </em>–<em>and intelligence is the capacity to perceive the essential, the true, the what is.”</em></mark></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Because if we don’t, we risk raising children who can recite facts by heart but cannot recognize the wonder in their own hearts. And between you and me, that would be far sadder than any forgotten boiled egg at the bottom of a lunch bag.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>References</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul class="wp-block-list"><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Krishnamurti on Education 2003</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>Education and the Significance of Life was first published in 1953</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><em>Note: All quotes mentioned in the article are by J. Krishnamurti.<strong></strong></em></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><mark class="has-inline-color has-luminous-vivid-orange-color"><strong>Priyanka Soman</strong> is an educator and writer with a keen interest in integrating the arts, sciences, and storytelling to create meaningful learning experiences. She can be reached at</mark> <a href="mailto:cspriyankaa@gmail.com">cspriyankaa@gmail.com</a>.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[<strong>Priyanka Soman</strong><br></strong>
In <em>“Tiffin Box Musings,”</em> the author gently reminds us that the most meaningful learning often slips in through unscripted moments – curious questions, shared laughter, and lived experiences. Drawing on J. Krishnamurti, she contrasts exam-driven “cleverness” with true intelligence: the freedom to perceive, feel, and think deeply without fear. Through stories of creative expression and collective vulnerability, the article invites educators to honour children’s natural wonder and move beyond factory-style schooling, nurturing minds – and hearts – awake to curiosity, compassion, and possibility.]]></excerpt:encoded>
